    {
      "id": "58",
      "source_id": "7",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "What is a practice that protects a network from VLAN hopping attacks?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "Change native VLAN to an unused VLAN ID",
        "B": "Enable dynamic ARP inspection",
        "C": "Configure an ACL to prevent traffic from changing VLANs",
        "D": "Implement port security on internet-facing VLANs"
      },
      "answer": [
        "A"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "VLAN Hopping: By altering the VLAN ID on packets encapsulated for trunking, an attacking\ndevice can send or receive packets on various VLANs, bypassing Layer 3 security measures. VLAN\nhopping can be accomplished by switch spoofing or double tagging. One of a popular type of VLAN\nHopping is\nDouble-Tagging attack:\nIn this attack, the attacking computer generates frames with two 802.1Q tags. The first tag\nmatches the native VLAN of the trunk port (VLAN 10 in this case), and the second matches the\nVLAN of a host it wants to attack (VLAN 20).\nWhen the packet from the attacker reaches Switch A, Switch A only sees the first VLAN 10 and it\nmatches with its native VLAN 10 so this VLAN tag is removed. Switch A forwards the frame out all\nlinks with the same native VLAN 10. Switch B receives the frame with an tag of VLAN 20 so it\nremoves this tag and forwards out to the Victim computer.\nNote: This attack only works if the trunk (between two switches) has the same native VLAN as the\nattacker. In other words, this attack is only successful if the attacker belongs to the native VLAN of\nthe trunk link. Another important point is, this attack is strictly one way as it is impossible to\nencapsulate the return packet.\nTo mitigate this type of attack, we can use VLAN access control lists (VACLs, which applies to all\ntraffic within a VLAN. We can use VACL to drop attacker traffic to specific victims/servers); or\nimplement Private VLANs; or keep the native VLAN of all trunk ports different from user VLANs.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Biện pháp nào bảo vệ mạng khỏi tấn công VLAN hopping?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Đổi native VLAN sang một VLAN ID không sử dụng",
        "B": "Bật dynamic ARP inspection",
        "C": "Cấu hình ACL để ngăn traffic thay đổi VLAN",
        "D": "Triển khai port security trên các VLAN hướng internet"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "59",
      "source_id": "8",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "Which technology can prevent client devices from arbitrarily connecting to the network without\nstate remediation?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "MAC Authentication Bypass",
        "B": "IP Source Guard",
        "C": "802.1x (PORT-BASED AUTHENTICATION)",
        "D": "802.11n"
      },
      "answer": [
        "C"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "The IEEE 802.1x standard defines a client-server-based access control and authentication protocol\nthat prevents unauthorized clients from connecting to a LAN through publicly accessible ports\nunless they are properly authenticated. The authentication server authenticates each client\nconnected to a switch port before making available any services offered by the switch or the LAN.\nUntil the client is authenticated, 802.1x access control allows only Extensible Authentication\nProtocol over LAN (EAPOL), Cisco Discovery Protocol (CDP), and Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)\ntraffic through the port to which the client is connected. After authentication is successful, normal\ntraffic can pass through the port.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Công nghệ nào có thể ngăn các thiết bị client kết nối tùy tiện vào mạng mà không qua kiểm tra trạng thái (state remediation)?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "MAC Authentication Bypass",
        "B": "IP Source Guard",
        "C": "802.1x (Xác thực dựa trên port)",
        "D": "802.11n"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "60",
      "source_id": "37",
      "type": "multi",
      "question": "Which two components comprise part of a PKI? (Choose two)",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "RSA token",
        "B": "clear-text password that authenticates connections",
        "C": "one of more CRLs",
        "D": "preshared key that authenticates connections",
        "E": "CA that grants certificates"
      },
      "answer": [
        "C",
        "E"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "PKI (or Public Key Infrastructure) is the framework of encryption and cybersecurity that protects\ncommunications between the server (your website) and the client (the users). Think about all the\ninformation, people, and services that your team communicates and works with. PKI is essential in\nbuilding a trusted and secure business environment by being able to verify and exchange data\nbetween various servers and users.\nThe components of a PKI include:\n+ public key\n+ private key\n+ Certificate Authority (CA)\n+ Certificate Store\n+ Certificate Revocation List (CRL)\n+ Hardware Security Module\nCertificate Authority (CA)\nThe CA generally handles all aspects of the certificate management for a PKI, including the phases\nof certificate lifecycle management.\nA CA issues certificates to be used to confirm that the subject imprinted on the certificate is the\nowner of the public key. In a PKI system, the client generates a public-private key pair. The public\nkey and information to be imprinted on the certificate are sent to the CA. The CA then creates a\ndigital certificate consisting of the user’s public key and certificate attributes. The certificate is\nsigned by the CA with its private key.\nCertificate Revocation List (CRL)\nA CRL is a list of certificates that have been revoked by the CA that issued them before they were\nset to expire. This is a helpful security feature if a device is stolen that contains a certificate. A\nRADIUS server only rejects a connection request from a device if the device’s certificate serial\nnumber is contained in the CRL. The Certificate Authority is the one that maintains this list, and\nthe RADIUS server periodically downloads this list by sending a query to the CA. There are two\ntypes of CRLs: A Delta CRL and a Base CRL.\nReference: https://www.securew2.com/blog/public-key-infrastructure-explained",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Hai thành phần nào là một phần của PKI? (Chọn hai)",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "RSA token",
        "B": "Mật khẩu clear-text để xác thực kết nối",
        "C": "Một hoặc nhiều CRL",
        "D": "Preshared key để xác thực kết nối",
        "E": "CA cấp chứng chỉ"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "61",
      "source_id": "59",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "An engineer must configure R1 for a new user account. The account must meet these\nrequirements:\n* It must be configured in the local database.\n* The username is engineer2\n* It must use the strongest password configurable.\nWhich command must the engineer configure on the router?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "R1(config)# username engineer2 algorithm-type scrypt secret test2021",
        "B": "R1(config)# username engineer2 secret 5 password $1$bUu$kZbBS1Pyh4QzwXyZ",
        "C": "R1(config)# username engineer2 privilege 1 password 7 test2021",
        "D": "R1(config)# username engineer2 secret 4 $1Sb1Ju$kZbBSlFyh4QxwXyZ"
      },
      "answer": [
        "A"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "Secret type 4 was determined to have a flaw and was removed in later versions of iOS. Type 4\nPasswords should never be used!\nSecret type 5 uses MD5 which is not secured.\nSecret type 9 – Scrypt and PBKDF2 (which can be used with “algorithm-type sha256”, but it is just\na small part of a much larger crypto algorithm) are much slower to compute and take longer to\nbrute force. Currently it is the strongest password configurable in Cisco devices.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Một kỹ sư phải cấu hình R1 cho một tài khoản người dùng mới. Tài khoản phải đáp ứng các yêu cầu sau:\n* Phải được cấu hình trong local database.\n* Username là engineer2\n* Phải sử dụng mật khẩu mạnh nhất có thể cấu hình.\nLệnh nào kỹ sư phải cấu hình trên router?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "R1(config)# username engineer2 algorithm-type scrypt secret test2021",
        "B": "R1(config)# username engineer2 secret 5 password $1$bUu$kZbBS1Pyh4QzwXyZ",
        "C": "R1(config)# username engineer2 privilege 1 password 7 test2021",
        "D": "R1(config)# username engineer2 secret 4 $1Sb1Ju$kZbBSlFyh4QxwXyZ"
      }
    },
