    {
      "id": "77",
      "source_id": "103",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "What is a practice that protects a network from VLAN hopping attacks?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "Implement port security on internet-facing VLANs.",
        "B": "Configure an ACL to prevent traffic from changing VLANs.",
        "C": "Assign all access ports to VLANs other than the native VLAN.",
        "D": "Enable dynamic ARP inspection."
      },
      "answer": [
        "C"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "VLAN Hopping: By altering the VLAN ID on packets encapsulated for trunking, an attacking\ndevice can send or receive packets on various VLANs, bypassing Layer 3 security measures. VLAN\nhopping can be accomplished by switch spoofing or double tagging. One of a popular type of VLAN\nHopping is\nDouble-Tagging attack:\nIn this attack, the attacking computer generates frames with two 802.1Q tags. The first tag\nmatches the native VLAN of the trunk port (VLAN 10 in this case), and the second matches the\nVLAN of a host it wants to attack (VLAN 20).\nWhen the packet from the attacker reaches Switch A, Switch A only sees the first VLAN 10 and it\nmatches with its native VLAN 10 so this VLAN tag is removed. Switch A forwards the frame out all\nlinks with the same native VLAN 10. Switch B receives the frame with an tag of VLAN 20 so it\nremoves this tag and forwards out to the Victim computer.\nNote: This attack only works if the trunk (between two switches) has the same native VLAN as the\nattacker. In other words, this attack is only successful if the attacker belongs to the native VLAN of\nthe trunk link. Another important point is, this attack is strictly one way as it is impossible to\nencapsulate the return packet.\nTo mitigate this type of attack, we can use VLAN access control lists (VACLs, which applies to all\ntraffic within a VLAN. We can use VACL to drop attacker traffic to specific victims/servers); or\nimplement Private VLANs; or keep the native VLAN of all trunk ports different from user VLANs.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Biện pháp nào bảo vệ mạng khỏi tấn công VLAN hopping?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Triển khai port security trên các VLAN hướng internet.",
        "B": "Cấu hình ACL để ngăn traffic thay đổi VLAN.",
        "C": "Gán tất cả access port vào VLAN khác với native VLAN.",
        "D": "Bật dynamic ARP inspection."
      }
    },
