        "B": "Cấu hình lệnh ip dhcp relay information option trên interface kết nối với DHCP server",
        "C": "Cấu hình lệnh ip dhcp relay information option trên interface kết nối với DHCP client",
        "D": "Cấu hình lệnh ip dhcp snooping trust trên interface kết nối với DHCP client"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "94",
      "source_id": "90",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "Refer to the exhibit.\nip arp inspection vlan 5-10\ninterface fastethernet0/1\nswitchport mode access\nswitchport access vlan 5\nWhat is the effect of this configuration?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "Egress traffic is passed only if the destination is a DHCP server.",
        "B": "All ingress and egress traffic is dropped because the interface is untrusted.",
        "C": "All ARP packets are dropped by the switch.",
        "D": "The switch discards all ingress ARP traffic with invalid MAC-to-IP address bindings."
      },
      "answer": [
        "D"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "Dynamic ARP inspection is an ingress security feature; it does not perform any egress checking.\nWireless Questions\nJanuary 10th, 2021Go to comments\nPremium Member: You can test your knowledge with these questions first via this link (via\nHTML).\nNote: If you are not sure about Wireless, please read our Wireless tutorial.\nQuick Wireless Summary\nWLAN Modes:\nWLAN has two basic modes of operation:\n* Ad-hoc mode: In this mode devices send data directly to each other without an AP.\n* Infrastructure mode: Connect to a wired LAN, supports two modes (service sets):\n+ Basic Service Set (BSS): uses only a single AP to create a WLAN\n+ Extended Service Set (ESS): uses more than one AP to create a WLAN, allows roaming\nin a larger area than a single AP. Usually there is an overlapped area between two APs to\nsupport roaming. The overlapped area should be more than 10% (from 10% to 15%) to\nallow users moving between two APs without losing their connections (called roaming).\nThe two adjacent APs should use non-overlapping channels to avoid interference. The\nmost popular non-overlapping channels are channels 1, 6 and 11 (will be explained later).\nRoaming: The ability to use a wireless device and be able to move from one access point’s\nrange to another without losing the connection.\nCisco Access Points (APs) can operate in one of two modes: autonomous or lightweight\n+ Autonomous: self-sufficient and standalone. Used for small wireless networks.\n+ Lightweight: A Cisco lightweight AP (LAP) has to join a Wireless LAN Controller\n(WLC) to function. LAP and WLC communicate with each other via a logical pair of\nCAPWAP tunnels.\n– Control and Provisioning for Wireless Access Point (CAPWAP) is an IETF standard\nprotocol which enables a WLC to manage multiple APs. CAPWAP is similar to LWAPP\nexcept the following differences:\n+ CAPWAP uses Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) for authentication and\nencryption to protect traffic between APs and controllers. LWAPP uses AES.\n+ CAPWAP has a dynamic maximum transmission unit (MTU) discovery mechanism.\n+ CAPWAP runs on UDP ports 5246 (control messages) and 5247 (data messages)\nSignal to Noise Ratio (SNR) is defined as the ratio of the transmitted power from the AP\nto the ambient (noise floor) energy present. To calculate the SNR value, we add the Signal\nValue to the Noise Value to get the SNR ratio. A positive value of the SNR ratio is always\nbetter.\nThe 2.4 GHz band is subdivided into multiple channels each allotted 22 MHz bandwidth\nand separated from the next channel by 5 MHz.\n-> A best practice for 802.11b/g/n WLANs requiring multiple APs is to use non-\noverlapping channels such as 1, 6, and 11.\nTypes of external antennas:\n+ Omnidirectional: Provide 360-degree coverage. Ideal in houses and office areas\n+ Directional: Focus the radio signal in a specific direction. Examples are the Yagi and\nparabolic dish\n+ Multiple Input Multiple Output (MIMO) – Uses multiple antennas (up to eight) to\nincrease bandwidth",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Tham khảo hình minh họa.\nip arp inspection vlan 5-10\ninterface fastethernet0/1\nswitchport mode access\nswitchport access vlan 5\nTác dụng của cấu hình này là gì?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Traffic egress chỉ được cho qua nếu đích là DHCP server.",
        "B": "Tất cả traffic ingress và egress bị loại bỏ vì interface không được tin cậy.",
        "C": "Tất cả ARP packet bị switch loại bỏ.",
        "D": "Switch loại bỏ tất cả ARP traffic ingress có liên kết MAC-to-IP không hợp lệ."
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "95",
      "source_id": "1",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "An engineer must configure a WLAN using the strongest encryption type for WPA2-PSK. Which\ncipher fulfills the configuration requirement?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "WEP",
        "B": "RC4",
        "C": "AES",
        "D": "TKIP"
      },
      "answer": [
        "C"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "Many routers provide WPA2-PSK (TKIP), WPA2-PSK (AES), and WPA2-PSK (TKIP/AES) as options.\nTKIP is actually an older encryption protocol introduced with WPA to replace the very-insecure WEP\nencryption at the time. TKIP is actually quite similar to WEP encryption. TKIP is no longer\nconsidered secure, and is now deprecated. In other words, you shouldn’t be using it.\nAES is a more secure encryption protocol introduced with WPA2 and it is currently the strongest\nencryption type for WPA2-PSK.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Một kỹ sư phải cấu hình WLAN sử dụng loại mã hóa mạnh nhất cho WPA2-PSK. Cipher nào đáp ứng yêu cầu cấu hình?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "WEP",
        "B": "RC4",
        "C": "AES",
        "D": "TKIP"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "96",
      "source_id": "2",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "Which unified access point mode continues to serve wireless clients after losing connectivity to the\nCisco Wireless LAN Controller?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "sniffer",
        "B": "mesh",
        "C": "flex connect",
        "D": "local"
      },
      "answer": [
        "C"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "In previous releases, whenever a FlexConnect access point disassociates from a controller, it\nmoves to the standalone mode. The clients that are centrally switched are disassociated. However,\nthe FlexConnect access point continues to serve locally switched clients. When the FlexConnect\naccess point rejoins the controller (or a standby controller), all clients are disconnected and are\nauthenticated again. This functionality has been enhanced and the connection between the clients\nand the FlexConnect access points are maintained intact and the clients experience seamless\nconnectivity. When both the access point and the controller have the same configuration, the\nconnection between the clients and APs is maintained.\nReference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/wireless/controller/7-\n4/configuration/guides/consolidated/b_cg74_CONSOLIDATED/b_cg74_CONSOLIDATED_chapter_0\n10001101.html",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Chế độ access point hợp nhất nào tiếp tục phục vụ các wireless client sau khi mất kết nối với Cisco Wireless LAN Controller?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Sniffer",
        "B": "Mesh",
        "C": "Flex connect",
        "D": "Local"
      }
    },
