      "id": "133",
      "source_id": "9",
      "type": "multi",
      "question": "What is the purpose of an SSID?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "It provides network security",
        "B": "It differentiates traffic entering access points",
        "C": "It identities an individual access point on a WLAN",
        "D": "It identifies a WLAN"
      },
      "answer": [
        "C",
        "D"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "Stands for “Service Set Identifier.” An SSID is a unique ID that consists of 32 characters and is\nused for naming wireless networks. When multiple wireless networks overlap in a certain location,\nSSIDs make sure that data gets sent to the correct destination.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Mục đích của SSID là gì?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Cung cấp bảo mật mạng",
        "B": "Phân biệt traffic đi vào các access point",
        "C": "Xác định một access point riêng lẻ trên WLAN",
        "D": "Xác định một WLAN"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "134",
      "source_id": "10",
      "type": "multi",
      "question": "What are two characteristics of an SSID? (Choose two)",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "It can be hidden or broadcast in a WLAN",
        "B": "It uniquely identifies an access point in a WLAN",
        "C": "It uniquely identifies a client in a WLAN",
        "D": "It is at most 32 characters long",
        "E": "It provides secured access to a WLAN"
      },
      "answer": [
        "A",
        "D"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "The SSID is a unique identifier that wireless networking devices use to establish and maintain\nwireless connectivity. The SSID can consist of up to 32 alphanumeric, case-sensitive, characters.\nWe can hide a SSID by choosing “Disabled” in the Basic Wireless Settings/Wireless/SSID Broadcast\nsection.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Hai đặc điểm nào của SSID? (Chọn hai)",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Nó có thể được ẩn hoặc broadcast trong WLAN",
        "B": "Nó xác định duy nhất một access point trong WLAN",
        "C": "Nó xác định duy nhất một client trong WLAN",
        "D": "Nó có tối đa 32 ký tự",
        "E": "Nó cung cấp quyền truy cập bảo mật vào WLAN"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "135",
      "source_id": "23",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "Refer to the exhibit.\nBetween which zones do wireless users expect to experience intermittent connectivity?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "between zones 1 and 2",
        "B": "between zones 2 and 5",
        "C": "between zones 3 and 4",
        "D": "between zones 3 and 6"
      },
      "answer": [
        "C"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "The 2.4 GHz band is subdivided into multiple channels each allotted 22 MHz bandwidth and\nseparated from the next channel by 5 MHz.\n-> A best practice for 802.11b/g/n WLANs requiring multiple APs is to use non-overlapping\nchannels such as 1, 6, and 11.\nIf you use channels that overlap, RF interference can occur.\nReference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless/aironet-340-series/8117-\nconnectivity.html\nIf other Wi-Fi sources such as neighboring wireless access points are using the same wireless\nchannel, this may cause intermittent connectivity issues.\nReference: https://arris.secure.force.com/consumers/articles/General_FAQs/SBG8300-\nTroubleshooting-Intermittent-Wi-Fi-Connections/?l=en_US&fs=RelatedArticle\nIn this question, both Zone 3 & Zone 4 use Channel 11 so interference can occur.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Tham khảo hình minh họa.\nGiữa các vùng nào người dùng wireless có thể gặp kết nối không ổn định?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Giữa vùng 1 và 2",
        "B": "Giữa vùng 2 và 5",
        "C": "Giữa vùng 3 và 4",
        "D": "Giữa vùng 3 và 6"
      }
    },
