    {
      "id": "150",
      "source_id": "60",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "An engineer is installing a new wireless printer with a static IP address on the Wi-Fi network.\nWhich feature must be enabled and configured to prevent connection issues with the printer?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "passive client",
        "B": "static IP tunneling",
        "C": "DHCP address assignment",
        "D": "client exclusion"
      },
      "answer": [
        "B"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "At times you may want to configure static IP addresses for wireless clients. When these wireless\nclients move about in a network, they could try associating with other controllers. If the clients try\nto associate with a controller that does not support the same subnet as static IP, the clients fail to\nconnect to the network. With WLC 7.0.116.0 you can enable dynamic tunneling of clients with\nstatic IP addresses.\nReference: https://mrncciew.com/2013/03/25/static-ip-clients-mobility/",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Một kỹ sư đang lắp đặt máy in wireless mới với địa chỉ IP tĩnh trên mạng Wi-Fi. Tính năng nào phải được bật và cấu hình để ngăn các sự cố kết nối với máy in?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Passive client",
        "B": "Static IP tunneling",
        "C": "Gán địa chỉ DHCP",
        "D": "Client exclusion"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "151",
      "source_id": "62",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "Refer to the exhibit. What must be configured to enable 802.11w on the WLAN?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "Set PMF to Required",
        "B": "Enable MAC Filtering",
        "C": "Enable WPA Policy",
        "D": "Set Fast Transition to Enabled"
      },
      "answer": [
        "A"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "Configuring 802.11w (GUI)\nProcedure\nStep 1 Choose WLANs > WLAN ID to open the WLANs > Edit page.\nStep 2 In the Security tab, choose the Layer 2 security tab.\nStep 3 From the Layer 2 Security drop-down list, choose WPA+WPA2.\nThe 802.11w IGTK Key is derived using the 4-way handshake, which means that it can only be\nused on WLANs that are configured for WPA2 security at Layer 2.\nNote: WPA2 is mandatory and encryption type must be AES. TKIP is not valid.\nStep 4 Choose the PMF state from the drop-down list\nThe following options are available:\nDisabled—Disables 802.11w MFP protection on a WLAN\nOptional—To be used if the client supports 802.11w.\nRequired—Ensures that the clients that do not support 802.11w cannot associate with the WLAN.\nReference: https://content.cisco.com/chapter.sjs?uri=/searchable/chapter/content/en/us/td/docs/\nwireless/controller/7-5/configuration-guide/b_cg75/b_cg75_chapter_01001100.html.xml\nNote: When you create a MAC address filter on WLCs, users are granted or denied access to the\nWLAN network based on the MAC address of the client they use\nFast Transition is 802.11r, not 802.11w.\nTherefore “Set PMF to Required” is the best choice.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Tham khảo hình minh họa. Cần cấu hình gì để bật 802.11w trên WLAN?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Đặt PMF thành Required",
        "B": "Bật MAC Filtering",
        "C": "Bật WPA Policy",
        "D": "Đặt Fast Transition thành Enabled"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "152",
      "source_id": "66",
      "type": "multi",
      "question": "Refer to the exhibit.\nA network engineer configures the Cisco WLC to authenticate local wireless clients against a\nRADIUS server. Which task must be performed to complete the process?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "Change the Server Status to Disabled",
        "B": "Select Enable next to Management",
        "C": "Select Enable next to Network User",
        "D": "Change the Support for CoA to Enabled"
      },
      "answer": [
        "B",
        "C"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "Check the Management button in order to allow the RADIUS Server to authenticate users who\nlogin to the the WLC.\nReference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/wireless-mobility/wlan-security/71989-\nmanage-wlc-users-radius.html",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Tham khảo hình minh họa.\nMột kỹ sư mạng cấu hình Cisco WLC để xác thực các wireless client cục bộ với RADIUS server. Tác vụ nào phải thực hiện để hoàn thành quá trình?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Đổi Server Status thành Disabled",
        "B": "Chọn Enable bên cạnh Management",
        "C": "Chọn Enable bên cạnh Network User",
        "D": "Đổi Support for CoA thành Enabled"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "153",
      "source_id": "78",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "What is a feature of WPA?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "802.1x authentication",
        "B": "preshared key",
        "C": "TKIP/MIC encryption",
        "D": "small Wi-Fi application"
      },
      "answer": [
        "C"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "WPA uses Michael, a special MIC designed to help with TKIP without requiring excessive\ncomputation.\nReference: https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/engineering/temporal-key-integrity-protocol\nWPA supports two authentication modes:\n– Personal\n– Enterprise\nWith personal mode, we use a pre-shared key. The pre-shared key is not used directly over the\nair. Instead, wireless clients and the AP use a four-way handshake that uses the pre-shared key as\ninput to generate encryption keys.\nEnterprise mode uses 802.1X and an authentication server, usually a RADIUS server.\nTherefore in this question, TKIP/MIC encryption is the best choice.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Tính năng nào của WPA?",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "Xác thực 802.1x",
        "B": "Preshared key",
        "C": "Mã hóa TKIP/MIC",
        "D": "Ứng dụng Wi-Fi nhỏ"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "154",
      "source_id": "102",
      "type": "multi",
      "question": "Which two wireless security standards use Counter Mode Cipher Block Chaining Message\nAuthentication Code Protocol for encryption and data integrity? (Choose two)",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "WPA2",
        "B": "WPA3",
        "C": "WEP",
        "D": "WPA",
        "E": "Wi-Fi 6"
      },
      "answer": [
        "A",
        "B"
      ],
      "answer_images": [],
      "explanation": "WPA2 mandates the use of a new protocol, counter mode with cipher-block chaining message\nauthentication protocol (CCMP). CCMP uses the AES block cipher, replacing the RC4 cipher used in\nwired equivalent privacy (WEP) and temporal key integrity protocol (TKIP).\nCCMP is a security protocol. It follows carefully designed steps that include the use of the AES\nspecified algorithm to encrypt sensitive data.\nCCMP-128 (AES-128 in CCM mode) is used as the minimum encryption algorithm in WPA3-\nPersonal mode.",
      "explanation_images": [],
      "question_vi": "Hai tiêu chuẩn bảo mật wireless nào sử dụng Counter Mode Cipher Block Chaining Message Authentication Code Protocol để mã hóa và đảm bảo tính toàn vẹn dữ liệu? (Chọn hai)",
      "options_vi": {
        "A": "WPA2",
        "B": "WPA3",
        "C": "WEP",
        "D": "WPA",
        "E": "Wi-Fi 6"
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "155",
      "source_id": "20",
      "type": "single",
      "question": "Which access point mode relies on a centralized controller tor management, roaming, and SSID\nconfiguration?",
      "question_images": [],
      "options": {
        "A": "repeater mode",
        "B": "bridge mode",
        "C": "lightweight mode",
        "D": "autonomous mode"
      },
      "answer": [
        "C"
